at cornell university will talk about new evidence on the linkages among agriculture nutrition and health with a special emphasis on south asia and or sub saharan africa currently lost in debate growing more food does not necessarily lead to better nutrition or health unless other things are put in place assistant professor eran bendavid from stanford's medical school infectious diseases will provide additional commentary bendavid was trained at harvard medical school and is currently a fse collaborator on a water related project that examines the links between food production health and nutrition per pinstrup andersen is babcock professor of food nutrition and public policy clark professor of entrepreneurship and professor of applied economics cornell university he was born in denmark and received his phd at oklahoma state university for many years he was the director general of the international food policy research institute in washington dc in 2001 he was named word food prize laureate pinstrup aandersen is a world renowned specialist on undernutrition health poverty and food location bechtel conference center encina hall 616 serra street stanford university stanford ca 94305 directions map fsi contact ashley dean parent research projects global food policy and food security symposium series fsi stanford fse series topics water south asia sub saharan africa search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages events of interest second and third generation human rights in africa health equity and aids treatment in africa helen stacy david katzenstein pdf+ second and third generation human rights in africa human rights and poverty in africa helen stacy dan banik paul h wise pdf+ is there a difference between organically and conventionally grown food a systematic review of the health benefits and harms crystal smith spangler margaret l brandeau dena m bravata vandana sundaram paul eschbach clay bavinger